import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Create a figure and axis

x = np.arange(3)
y = [2.5, 4.5, 6.5]

# Display the plot

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10.0, 6.0))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)

# Create a 3D bar chart
x = np.arange(1, 7)
y = np.arange(1, 7)
x, y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
z = np.random.rand(6, 6)*95 + 5

ax.bar3d(x.ravel(), y.ravel(), np.zeros_like(z).ravel(), 1, 1, z.ravel(), shade=True)

plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Data for plotting
labels = ['Q1', 'Q2', 'Q3', 'Q4']
q1 = [275, 290, 280, 260]
q2 = [280, 295, 290, 270]
q3 = [290, 300, 305, 285]
q4 = [300, 310, 315, 295]

x = np.arange(len(labels))  # the label locations
width = 0.2  # the width of the bars

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8.0, 6.0))
rects1 = ax.bar(x - width, q1, width, label='Tesla')
rects2 = ax.bar(x, q2, width, label='Benz')
rects3 = ax.bar(x + width, q3, width, label='BYD')
rects4 = ax.bar(x + 2*width, q4, width, label='Porsche')

# Add some text for labels, title, and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.
ax.set_ylabel('Earnings ($1000)')
ax.set_title('Quarterly Earnings')
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.legend()

def autolabel(rects):
    """Attach a text label above each bar in *rects*, displaying its height."""
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        ax.annotate('{0:.0f}'.format(height),
                    xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),
                    xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset.
                    textcoords="offset points",
                    ha='center', va='bottom')

autolabel(rects1)
autolabel(rects2)
autolabel(rects3)
autolabel(rects4)

plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8.0, 5.0))

# Data for plotting
labels = ['1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6']
men_means = [49.7, 48.8, 48.5, 48.4, 48.3, 48.2]
women_means = [48.7, 48.6, 48.4, 48.3, 48.2, 48.1]

x = range(len(labels))  # the label locations
width = 0.35  # the width of the bars

rects1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, men_means, width, label='Men')
rects2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, women_means, width, label='Women')

# Add some text for labels, title and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.
ax.set_ylabel('Scores')
ax.set_title('Human Labeling and Agreement Bias Checking')
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.legend()

def autolabel(rects):
    """Attach a text label above each bar in *rects*, displaying its height."""
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        ax.annotate('{}'.format(height),
                    xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),
                    xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset.
                    textcoords="offset points",
                    ha='center', va='bottom')

autolabel(rects1)
autolabel(rects2)

plt.show()

x2 = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)

# Add a color bar to the plot

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

labels = ['BART', 'RoBERTa', 'DistilBERT', 'XLNet', 'Electra', 'Albert', 'DeBERTa', 'Llama2']
ground_truth = [64.5, 58.7, 60.9, 62.1, 59.4, 60.2, 61.1, 57.8]
weak_labels = [54.2, 48.5, 50.3, 51.4, 49.1, 50.2, 51.1, 48.6]

x = np.arange(len(labels))  # the label locations
width = 0.35  # the width of the bars

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10.0, 3.0))
rects1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, ground_truth, width, label='Ground-Truth labels')
rects2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, weak_labels, width, label='Weak labels')

ax.set_ylabel('Accuracy (%)')
ax.set_title('Accuracy of different models')
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.legend()

def autolabel(rects):
    """Attach a text label above each bar in *rects*, displaying its height."""
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        ax.annotate('{:.1f}'.format(height),
                    xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),
                    xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset.
                    textcoords="offset points",
                    ha='center', va='bottom')

autolabel(rects1)
autolabel(rects2)

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import networkx as nx

G.add_node(2)
G.add_node(3)
G.add_node(4)
G.add_node(5)
G.add_node(6)
G.add_node(7)
G.add_node(8)
G.add_node(9)
G.add_node(10)

G.add_edge(1, 2)
G.add_edge(1, 3)
G.add_edge(2, 4)
G.add_edge(2, 5)
G.add_edge(3, 6)
G.add_edge(3, 7)
G.add_edge(4, 8)
G.add_edge(4, 9)
G.add_edge(5, 10)
G.add_edge(6, 10)
G.add_edge(7, 10)
G.add_edge(8, 10)
G.add_edge(9, 10)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Data for plotting
nominations = [50, 100, 150, 200, 250]
record_of_the_year = [19.4, 17.3, 16.2, 15.1, 14.0]
album_of_the_year = [18.3, 16.2, 15.1, 14.0, 12.9]
song_of_the_year = [17.2, 15.1, 14.0, 12.9, 11.8]
best_new_artist = [16.1, 14.0, 12.9, 11.8, 10.7]
best_pop_song_performance = [15.0, 13.9, 12.8, 11.7, 10.6]

# Create a bar chart with the specified data and labels
plt.bar(nominations, record_of_the_year, color='red', label='Record of the Year')
plt.bar(nominations, album_of_the_year, bottom=record_of_the_year, color='orange', label='Album of the Year')
plt.bar(nominations, song_of_the_year, bottom=[i+j for i,j in zip(record_of_the_year, album_of_the_year)], color='yellow', label='Song of the Year')
plt.bar(nominations, best_new_artist, bottom=[i+j+k for i,j,k in zip(record_of_the_year, album_of_the_year, song_of_the_year)], color='pink', label='Best New Artist')
plt.bar(nominations, best_pop_song_performance, bottom=[i+j+k+l for i,j,k,l in zip(record_of_the_year, album_of_the_year, song_of_the_year, best_new_artist)], color='yellow', label='Best Pop Song Performance')

# Set the title of the plot
plt.title('Grammy Nominations Across Expanded Categories 2019-2023')

# Set the x-axis label
plt.xlabel('Number of Nominations')

# Set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Number of Nominations')

# Add a legend to the plot
plt.legend()

# Set the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(12.0, 8.0))

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5.0, 5.0))
ax.set_title('XNLI (speed-up ratio: 4)')
ax.set_xlabel('es')
ax.set_ylabel('en')

# Create a list of colors for each bar
colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue']

# Create a list of labels for each bar
labels = ['fr', 'hi', 'ru', 'th', 'tr', 'ur', 'vi', 'sw', 'bg', 'ar', 'zh']

# Create a list of values for each bar
values = [20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200, 220]

# Create a list of angles for each bar
angles = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, len(labels), endpoint=False).tolist()

# Add a '0' at the end of the list to close the circle
angles += angles[:1]
values += values[:1]

# Plot the bars
ax.plot(angles, values, 'o-', linewidth=2, markersize=10)

# Set the color of each bar
for i, label in enumerate(labels):
    ax.fill(angles[i:i+2], values[i:i+2], colors[i], alpha=0.25)

# Set the tick labels
ax.set_xticks(angles[:-1])
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)

plt.show()

plt.show()

ax.set_title('Comparison of Scores with and without Memory')

ax.set_title('Memory Impact on User Experience')

ax.set_ylabel('Score')
